        <div n="911-79L1" type="poem"><head type="note" n="1" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-headnote-1"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-headnote-1-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-headnote-1-line-group-1-line-1">Written in or about the Year 1724.</l></lg></head><head type="note" n="2" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-headnote-2"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-headnote-2-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-headnote-2-line-group-1-line-1">XXVI. TO LADY CARTERET.</l></lg></head><head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-headnote-3"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1">BY DR. SWIFT.</l></lg></head>
      <lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-1"><hi rend="display-initial">F</hi>ROM India's burning clime I·'m brought,</l><l n="2" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-2"> With cooling gales like Zephyrs fraught.</l><l n="3" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-3"> Not Iris, when she paints the sky,</l><l n="4" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-4"> Can shew more different hue than I;</l><l n="5" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-5"> Nor can she change her form so fast,</l><l n="6" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-6"> I·'m now a sail, and now a mast.</l><l n="7" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-7"> I here am red, and there am green,</l><l n="8" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-8"> A beggar there, and here a queen.</l><l n="9" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-9"> I sometimes live in house of hair,</l><l n="10" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-10"> And oft' in hand of lady fair.</l><l n="11" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-11"> I please the young, I grace the old,</l><l n="12" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-12"> And am at once both hot and cold.</l><l n="13" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-13"> Say what I am then, if you can,</l><l n="14" xml:id="spp-911-79L1-line-14"> And find the rhyme, and you·'re the man.911-79L1   </l></lg></div>
